qx|4.2|
at|^b@2^z@3|
cs|5|cp|6|fp|4|
fp||cp||at|
Hopefully you have been convinced that Jacoby transfer bids are an excellent convention. However, it would be a mistake to think that there are no disadvantages to using Jacoby transfers. In fact, almost every convention suffers from the same disadvantage:

|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


cs|2|At|^-{ Replacing a natural bid with an artificial bid 
 means that the natural bid is no longer available. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


cs|1|at|In the case of Jacoby transfers after a 1NT opening bid, the critical natural bid that is being replaced by an artificial bid is the 2@D response to 1NT:

^k|ia|o1n!2d|at|

|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


at|If Jacoby transfer bids are not being used, the 2@D response to a 1NT opening bid is available as a signoff bid in diamonds. If a partnership is using Jacoby, however, the 2@D response becomes a transfer to hearts. As such, there is no way for the responder to sign off in 2@D in the SAYC bidding system when his partner opens the bidding with 1NT.

|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


at|Although you may not have thought about this before, you have seen other examples of this sort of tradeoff. Consder the use of the Stayman 2@C convention. If a partnership is using Stayman (as almost every partnership does), they have no way to sign off in 2@C after a 1NT opening bid.

|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


tb||


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|2|at|
^-{ For a convention to be effective, the gain from using that convention must be 
 greater than the loss that comes from replacing a natural bid with an artificial bid. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


cs|1|at|^D{ |ia|o1n!2c|at| } ^O{ |ia|o1n!2d|at| }

In the judgment of bridge authorities, the benefits of using the Stayman convention and Jacoby transfer bids are more than enough to compensate for the fact that the responder to a 1NT opening bid can no longer sign off in 2@C or 2@D when these conventions are being used. That is why almost all serious bridge players prefer to use both of these conventions with their regular partners. Still, these players will sometimes be dealt a hand like one of the following:
|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


n#|5|cs|3|at|^E{ |ih|ps6hj5dt743cjt8742|at| } |n#|s|at|^P{ |ih|ps954h5dqj98652c53|at| }

|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


at|These are both weak and unbalanced hands containing long minor suits. If your partner opened 1NT and you were dealt one of these hands, you would like to get out of 1NT and into the safety of playing with your long minor as trump at as low a level as possible. Neither of these hands rates to win very many tricks in a notrump contract, but both of these hands rate to win several tricks with their respective long minors as trump.

|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|ht|c|n#|3|at|^k|ia|o1n!2s|at|

|cs|3|at|^E{ |ih|ps6hj5dt743cjt8742|at| } |n#|s|at|^P{ |ih|ps954h5dqj98652c53|at| }

|cs|2|At|^-{ There is no way to sign off in 2@C or 2@D after a 1NT opening in the SAYC bidding system, 
 but it is possible to sign off in 3@C or 3@D. To do this, respond 2@S to your partner's 1NT. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


at|Yes, this 2@S response to 1NT is another new convention, but given that we are using Jacoby transfer bids, this particular convention does not really replace a useful natural bid. 

If we were not using Jacoby, the 2@S response to a 1NT opening bid would be a signoff bid. Now that we are using Jacoby transfers there is no need to use the 2@S bid this way. We already have a way to sign off in 2@S - by bidding 2@H as a Jacoby transfer and passing when our partner completes the transfer.

|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ When Jacoby transfers are being used, the 2@S response to 1NT is ^*Ifreed up^*N since it is no
 longer needed as a natural bid. SAYC uses the 2@S response to sign off in 3@C or 3@D. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
So how do we get from 2@S to 3@C or 3@D?

|cs|1|ht|d|at|^k|ia|o1n2s?|at|

|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


ht|d|cs|1|at|^k|ia|o1n2s!3c|at|

|n#|5|at|
|cs|2|At|^-{ In SAYC the 2@S response to a 1NT opening bid asks the opener to bid 3@C. Responder 
 will pass 3@C if his long minor suit is clubs and bid 3@D if his long minor suit is diamonds. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


n#|3|cs|3|at|^^^^^^^B{ |ih|ps6hj5dt743cjt8742|at| }    @2
|ht|n|n#|7|at|If the responder has the first example hand we have been considering (a weak hand with long clubs), he will respond 2@S to 1NT. The 1NT opener will rebid 3@C and the responder will then pass. 3@C will become the final contract.
^b@2
|ht|d|cs|1|at|^k|ia|o1n2s3c!p|at|

|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


cs|3|ht|u|n#|5|at|^B{ |ih|ps954h5dqj98652c53|at| }    @2

|ht|v|at|If the responder has the second example hand (a weak hand with long diamonds), he will similarly respond 2@S to 1NT. The 1NT opener will rebid 3@C as before, but this time the responder will bid 3@D instead of passing. The opener must now pass and 3@D will become the final contract.
^b@2
|ht|d|cs|1|at|^k|ia|o1n2s3c!3d!p|at|

|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
To summarize, here is how the 2@S response to 1NT works in the SAYC bidding system:

|cs|1|at|^D{ |ia|o1n2s3cp|at| } ^O{ |ia|o1n2s3c3dp|at| }

|cs|3|at|^E{ |ih|ps6hj5dt743cjt8742|at| } |n#|s|at|^P{ |ih|ps954h5dqj98652c53|at| }

|cs|2|at|^-{ A 2@S response to a 1NT opening bid forces the opener to rebid 3@C. The responder will 
 pass 3@C if he has long clubs and rebid 3@D (which the opener will pass) with long diamonds. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Unlike Jacoby transfers where the opener may super-accept with an appropriate 
 hand, the opener has no such option over the 2@S response to his 1NT opening bid. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


at|In the case of the 2@S response to 1NT, the opener must ^*Ialways^*N rebid 3@C. Furthermore, if the responder bids 3@D next, the opener must ^*Ialways^*N pass. It does not matter how good or bad the opener's hand is for either minor. He must do as he is told when this convention is invoked!

|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
There are 2 main reasons why the opener should do exactly as he is told when the responder bids 2@S over 1NT:

|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 1. The 2@S response is always based on a hand that wants to sign off in 3 of a minor. 
 The opener has already described his hand - he should respect his partner's judgment! }

|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ 2. In the SAYC bidding system the responder can bid 3@C or 3@D directly 
 over 1NT to describe a hand with invitational strength and a long minor suit. }

|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


at|^-Consider the following hands:
|n#|5|cs|3|at|^E{ |ih|ps74h95d752caqt976|at| } |n#|s|at|^P{ |ih|ps9h863dkqj943c852|at| }

|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


at|Each of these hands has 6 HCP |
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


at|and 2 long suit points for their respective 6-card minor suits. 9 total points is enough for a game invitation opposite a 15-17 HCP 1NT opening bid. If the opener has an appropriate hand (specifically with a fitting high card in the responder's long minor and stoppers in the other 3 suits), 3NT rates to be a good contract. Otherwise, a partial with a long minor suit as trump will be a reasonable place to be.

|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ When the responder has such a hand, he needs the opener's help to select the contract. }

|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|at|
^D{ |ia|o1n!3c|at| } ^O{ |ia|o1n!3d|at| }
|n#|7|cs|3|at|^E{ |ih|ps74h95d752caqt976|at| } |n#|s|at|^P{ |ih|ps9h863dkqj943c852|at| }

|cs|2|at|^-{ In the SAYC bidding system, direct jumps to 3@C and 3@D over a 1NT opening are used 
 to describe invitational strength hands with a strong 6-card suit in the suit that was bid. }

|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ When the responder bids 3@C or 3@D over a 1NT opening, the opener should bid 3NT if 
 he thinks he can win 9 tricks in notrump opposite such a hand. Otherwise, he should pass. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


at|In most situations in bridge, an invitational bid is a suggestion that a game contract will be a good bet only if the partner of the player who made that bid has a maximum hand given the bidding to that point. This situation is different. There are some minimum hands with which the opener should bid 3NT over a 3@C or 3@D response to his 1NT opening and there are some maximum hands with which the opener should pass in this situation.

|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ The opener's decision as to whether or not he should bid 3NT after a 3@C or 3@D response to
 his 1NT opening is more about judgment than it is about whether he is minimum or maximum. }

|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|3|ht|b|
at|^C{ |ih|psak32hjt76da6ck84|at| } |cs|1|n#|5|at|^N{ |ia|o1n3c!3N|at| }

|n#|7|at|For example, the hand shown above has only 15 HCP making it a minimum for a 15-17 1NT opening bid.  Nevertheless, once this hand opens 1NT and the responder bids 3@C (suggesting an invitational hand with a strong 6-card club suit), the opener should go on to 3NT.

|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


cs|3|at|^^^^^^^C{ |ih|ps74h95d752caqt976|at| }    @2
|ht|n|at|The reason is that the opener should expect to make 3NT opposite a typical hand for the responder like the one we have been considering. 
^b@2

|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


n#|3|at|The opener's @CK is a very big card. He should know that his @CK means that there is an excellent chance that 6 club tricks will be available in notrump. |
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


at|His @SA, @SK, and @DA will provide the other 3 winners that the partnership will need to succeed in 3NT. Furthermore, these cards will also provide stoppers in their respective suits. |
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


at|Finally note that the opener's heart holding, although nothing special, is sufficient to prevent the defenders from getting rich in that suit.

|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ The opener has a good reason to bid 3NT - he expects to succeed in that game contract! }

|
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|3|ht|b|
at|^C{ |ih|psakq5hj42dt2caqj7|at| } |cs|1|n#|5|at|^N{ |ia|o1n3d!p|at| }

|n#|7|at|This example hand represents the other side of the coin. Here, the opener has 17 HCP - an absolute maximum for his opening bid. Still the opener's judgment should tell him to pass when his partner responds with 3@D over his 1NT.

|
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


cs|3|at|^^^^^^^C{ |ih|ps9h863dkqj943c852|at| }    @2
|ht|m|at|The reason is that the opener should expect 3NT to fail if his partner has a hand like the example hand that we have been considering.

^b@2
|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


n#|5|at|The opener's weak holding in diamonds, his partner's long suit, is especially worrisome for notrump purposes. Assuming the defenders are familiar with the hold up play, they will be able to prevent the declarer in notrump from utilizing the responder's fine diamonds. |
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


at|Furthermore, opener's lack of a heart stopper is another reason to suspect that 3NT will fail.

|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ The opener has a good reason to pass 3@D - he expects that 3NT will fail and that 3@D will 
 have a chance. It turns out that 3@D is a big favorite opposite responder's example hand. }

|
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|at|
^B{ |ia|o1n!2s|at| } 

^B{ |ia|o1n!3c|at| } 

^B{ |ia|o1n!3d|at| } 

|

ht|b|at|^L @2The 3 bidding sequences that you see to the left are used by the responder after a 1NT opening bid to describe hands will long minor suits.

|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


at|The 2@S response is used to sign off in either 3@C or 3@D. The direct 3@C and 3@D responses are used to describe hands with invitational strength containing strong 6-card minor suits. When the responder uses either of these latter two bids, the opener is being asked to choose between playing 3 of a minor or 3NT.

^b@2
|
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ When the responder uses any of these bids, he promises at least 6 cards in his long minor. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


at|Recall that for the responder to use a Jacoby transfer bid (his primary tool for responding to 1NT when he has a long major suit), he needs only 5 cards in the suit that he transfers to. The reason that a 6th card is required in order to use the 2@S, 3@C, or 3@D responses to 1NT is that these bids force the partnership to the 3-level. If the partnership ends up playing in 3@C or 3@D (as they often will if any of these bids are used), that extra trump will usually result in an extra trick.

|
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


cs|4|At|^-{ When the responder's longest suit is a 5-card minor, he will usually be better off to ignore
 his minor and remain in notrump (by either passing 1NT or by raising to 2NT or 3NT). }
^-
|
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3We have now discussed many of responder's possible actions in the SAYC bidding system after his partner opens the bidding with 1NT. Some good news for you is that all of the other responses to 1NT have almost the same meaning in SAYC as they do in the bidding system that was taught in the original Learn to Play Bridge program.

We will not go into much detail about most of these bids here since these sequences were covered extensively in the original Learn to Play Bridge program. For the sake of completeness, however, a summary of the meanings of other responses to a 1NT opening bid will now be presented. First, here are the meanings of various notrump responses to a 1NT opening bid:

|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 2NT - Invitational to 3NT. Opener passes with a minimum and bids 3NT with a maximum. }

|
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ 3NT - a signoff bid. The opener should always pass. }

|
pg| ***** 48 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ 4NT - Invitational to 6NT. Opener passes with a minimum and bids 6NT with a maximum. }

|
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ 5NT - Invitational to 7NT. Opener bids 6NT with a minimum and bids 7NT with a maximum. }

|
pg| ***** 50 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ 6NT - a signoff bid. The opener should always pass. }

|
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ 7NT - a signoff bid. There is nowhere left for the opener to go! }

|
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


at|^-If the reponder has less than game invitational strength, no 5-card (or longer) major suit, and no 6-card (or longer) minor suit, he should pass his partner's 1NT opening bid. 1NT may not always be the best contract in this case, but it is the best you can do using SAYC.|
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|at|
We have already studied the various 2-level suit responses to a 1NT opening bid in SAYC. 2@C is Stayman, 2@D and 2@H are Jacoby transfer bids, and 2@S asks the opener to bid 3@C for the purposes of signing off in either 3@C or 3@D. We have also covered the direct 3@C and 3@D responses to 1NT.

If you were paying very close attention, you might have noticed that something was missing during our extensive study of Jacoby transfer bids: the way that Jacoby transfers are used in SAYC, the responder has no way of suggesting interest in slam with a 6-card (or longer) major suit. The responder has a lot of options after he uses a Jacoby transfer and the opener completes the transfer, but describing a strong hand with a long major suit is not in his bag of tricks.

|
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


cs|1|at|^D{ |ia|o1n!3h|at| } ^O{ |ia|o1n!3s|at| }

|cs|2|at|^-{ SAYC uses the direct 3@H and 3@S responses to a 1NT opening to suggest at least 6 
 cards in the suit that was bid and a hand that is strong enough to be interested in slam. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 55 ***** |


cs|3|At|^-{ When the responder to a 1NT opening has a 5-card (or longer) major, he almost always 
 responds with a Jacoby transfer. The 3@H and 3@S responses are an exception to this. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


 
at|The only other exception to this principle is when the responder has 5-4 in the majors and a hand with at least invitational strength. As we have seen, the responder to a 1NT opening bid should use Stayman (and not transfer) when he has this sort of hand.

|
pg| ***** 57 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Here are some examples of hands that would use the 3@H and 3@S responses to a 1NT opening:

|cs|1|at|^D{ |ia|o1n!3h|at| } ^O{ |ia|o1n!3s|at| }
|n#|7|cs|3|at|^E{ |ih|psS54haqj932dat6ck9|at| } |n#|s|at|^P{ |ih|psakj9862hk5caqcd84|at| }

|
pg| ***** 58 ***** |


at|The first hand has 14 HCP |
pg| ***** 59 ***** |


at|and 2 long suit points for the 6-card heart suit. A small slam is a definite possibility and the responder should express this by jumping to 3@H over his partner's 1NT opening bid. This bid promises at least 6 cards in hearts so the opener will know that he does not require 3-card support to make hearts an adequate trump suit.

|
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


at|The second hand is so strong that even a grand slam might be possible. This hand has 17 HCP |
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


at|and 3 long suit points for the 7-card spade suit. With 20 total points facing 15-17 HCP in the opener's hand, the partnership is certain to reach at least a small slam contract. 

|
pg| ***** 62 ***** |


at|When the responder bids 3@H or 3@S directly over his partner's 1NT opening bid, the opener can raise to game if he does not like his hand for slam purposes. If the opener's hand is maximum, contains good trump support, and/or a lot of Aces and Kings, he can cooperate with the responder's slam investigation by cuebidding an Ace in a new suit.

|
pg| ***** 63 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
While the meanings of the 3@H and 3@S responses to a 1NT opening bid in SAYC are similar to those that were presented in Learn to Play Bridge there are 2 important differences:

|cs|1|at|^D{ |ia|o1n!3h|at| } ^O{ |ia|o1n!3s|at| }

|
pg| ***** 64 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 1. In SAYC these bids promise at least 6 cards in the responder's major suit. In the
 other bidding system, these bids can be based on suits with only 5 cards in them. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 65 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 2. In SAYC these bids suggest that at least a small slam might be possible. In the other
 bidding system, these bids are forcing to game, but they do not promise slam interest. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 66 ***** |


at|In other words, the 3@H and 3@S responses to 1NT are more narrowly defined (both in terms of strength and in terms of distribution) in SAYC than they are in most bidding systems that do not use Jacoby transfers. The reason for this is that when Jacoby transfers are being used, a lot of the hands that would respond 3@H or 3@S in the absence of transfers can be bid more accurately with the help of Jacoby.
|
pg| ***** 67 ***** |


n#|5|cs|3|at|^^^^^B{ |ih|pskqt94h6daj32ct65|at|}    @2
|ht|q|n#|7|at|For example, this hand calls for a 3@S response to 1NT if Jacoby transfers are not being used. With transfers, however, there is a better way to bid this hand. Start with 2@H as a transfer to spades and followup with 3@D (a natural game forcing bid) when the opener completes the transfer. 
|
pg| ***** 68 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|7|cs|1|at|^^^-{ The only other suit response to a 1NT opening that is defined in SAYC is 4@C. As in 
 most bidding systems the 4@C response to 1NT is the Gerber convention in SAYC. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 69 ***** |


at|Recall that the Gerber convention is used to asked for Aces when the last bid made was in notrump. The Blackwood 4NT convention is used to ask for Aces in most bidding sequences, but a 4NT response to a 1NT opening is a quantitative raise, not Blackwood. The Gerber convention was designed to give the responder an easy way to ask for Aces in bidding sequences in which Blackwood is not available. Here is a reminder of the responses to Gerber:

|
pg| ***** 70 ***** |


cs|3|at|^J{ 4@D - Either 0 Aces or all 4 Aces 
^J 4@H - 1 Ace
^J 4@S - 2 Aces
^J 4NT - 3 Aces }

|
pg| ***** 71 ***** |


at|After the opener responds to Gerber, the responder can either sign off in any contract or continue with 5@C to ask the opener how many Kings he was dealt. The opener responds to the King ask as follows:
|
pg| ***** 72 ***** |


cs|2|at|^^^J{ 5@D - Either 0 Kings or all 4 Kings 
^J 5@H - 1 King
^J 5@S - 2 Kings
^J 5NT - 3 Kings }

|
pg| ***** 73 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Remember, the Gerber 4@C bid is used to ask for Aces and Kings after a 1NT opening bid! 
 A 4NT response to 1NT is a quantitative raise - it is not the Blackwood convention. }
|
pg| ***** 74 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Some bridge players get confused when it comes to asking for Aces and Kings after either Stayman or a Jacoby transfer bid has been used. Here are some guidelines that can be used to clarify this subject:

|
pg| ***** 75 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ If the responder uses Stayman or Jacoby and then rebids 4NT, that bid 
 is always a quantitative raise (as opposed to the Blackwood convention). }
^-
|
pg| ***** 76 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ If the responder rebids 4@C after using Stayman that bid is always Gerber. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 77 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ The responder has no way to ask for Aces with his rebid after a Jacoby transfer. To show 
